Vitamin D<sub>2</sub>, or [[ergocalciferol]] found in [[fungus|fungi]], is synthesized from [[viosterol]], which in turn is activated when ultraviolet light stimulates [[ergosterol]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/589256_4 |title=Access |publisher=Medscape |accessdate=2012-06-13}}</ref>

Human [[bioavailability]] of vitamin D<sub>2</sub> from vitamin D<sub>2</sub>-enhanced button mushrooms via UV-B irradiation is effective in improving vitamin D status and not different from a vitamin D<sub>2</sub> supplement.<ref name="pmid21540874">{{cite journal | author = Urbain P, Singler F, Ihorst G, Biesalski HK, Bertz H | title = Bioavailability of vitamin D₂ from UV-B-irradiated button mushrooms in healthy adults deficient in serum 25-hydroxyvitamin D: a randomized controlled trial | journal = Eur J Clin Nutr | volume = 65 | issue = 8 | pages = 965–71 | year = 2011 | month = August | pmid = 21540874 | doi = 10.1038/ejcn.2011.53 }}</ref> from UV-irradiated yeast baked into bread is bioavailable.<ref name="pmid21332187">{{cite journal | author = Hohman EE, Martin BR, Lachcik PJ, Gordon DT, Fleet JC, Weaver CM | title = Bioavailability and efficacy of vitamin D2 from UV-irradiated yeast in growing, vitamin D-deficient rats | journal = J. Agric. Food Chem. | volume = 59 | issue = 6 | pages = 2341–6 | year = 2011 | month = March | pmid = 21332187 | pmc = 3235799 | doi = 10.1021/jf104679c }}</ref> By visual assessment or using a chromometer, no significant discoloration of irradiated mushrooms, as measured by the degree of "whiteness", was observed.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Koyyalamudi SR, Jeong SC, Song CH, Cho KY, Pang G | title = Vitamin D<sub>2</sub> formation and bioavailability from Agaricus bisporus button mushrooms treated with ultraviolet irradiation | journal = J Agric Food Chem | volume = 57 | issue = 8 | pages = 3351–5 | year = 2009 | pmid = 19281276 | doi = 10.1021/jf803908q }}</ref> Claims have been made that a normal serving (approx. 3 oz or 1/2 cup, or 60 grams) of fresh mushrooms treated with ultraviolet light have increased vitamin D content to levels up to 80 micrograms,<ref>{{cite web|author=Using Fresh Mushrooms as a Source of Vitamin D |url=http://www.fitday.com/fitness-articles/nutrition/healthy-eating/using-fresh-mushrooms-as-a-source-of-vitamin-d.html |title=Using Fresh Mushrooms as a Source of Vitamin D / Nutrition / Healthy Eating |publisher=Fitday.com |accessdate=2012-06-13}}</ref> or 2700 IU if exposed to just 5 minutes of UV light after being harvested.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Bringing Mushrooms Out of the Dark |date=April 18, 2006 |url =http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/12370708|work =MSNBC|accessdate = 2007-08-06}}</ref>

